# Project Standards

## Web Standards

- Use modern ES module syntax (`import`/`export`) — no CommonJS (`require`/`module.exports`).
- Write semantic HTML (`<main>`, `<section>`, `<header>`, `<nav>`, etc.) over generic `<div>` soup.
- Follow accessibility best practices: meaningful `alt` text, proper heading hierarchy, ARIA attributes where needed, keyboard-navigable interactive elements.
- Use responsive design principles — layouts should work across viewport sizes.
- Prefer native browser APIs over third-party libraries when the native option is well-supported.

## TypeScript

- All source code lives in `assets/js/` and must be TypeScript (`.ts`).
- Enable and respect `strict` mode — no `any` unless absolutely unavoidable and explicitly justified.
- Prefer `unknown` over `any` when the type is truly not known; narrow before use.
- Add type annotations to all function signatures (parameters and return types).
- Shared types and interfaces belong in `assets/js/contracts/`.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; use `type` for unions, intersections, and utility types.
- Prefer modular ES imports/exports.

## Code Quality

- One responsibility per file — keep files small and focused.
- Use descriptive names for functions, variables, and types. Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood (`id`, `url`, `html`).
- Keep business logic out of the UI layer — UI files handle DOM interaction only.
- Avoid deep nesting; prefer early returns and guard clauses.
- Comments should explain *why*, not *what*. Do not narrate obvious code.
- No hardcoded magic numbers or strings — extract to named constants.
- Prefer pure functions where possible; isolate side effects.
- Consistent naming and structure across the codebase.

## CSS

- All styles live in `assets/css/styles.css`.
- Organise with clear section comments:

```css
/* =========================
   Section Name
========================= */
```

- Use CSS custom properties (`--var`) for colours, spacing, and typography.
- Minimise duplication — extract shared values into variables.
- Mobile-first responsive approach using relative units and media queries.

## Project Structure

```
assets/js/
  contracts/      # Shared types and interfaces
  calculator/     # Core calculation logic (pure functions)
  data/           # Static resource definitions
  formatters/     # Output/data transformation
  app/            # State management and persistence
  ui/             # DOM interaction (no business logic)
```

Expand as needed, but maintain the same philosophy: group by concern, not by file type.

- `service.ts` — core logic
- `utils.ts` — reusable helpers
- `formatters/` — output/data formatting
- `contracts/` — shared types and interfaces

## Goal

Build a scalable, maintainable resource calculator that:

- Can be easily extended with new resource chains
- Keeps logic decoupled from UI
- Is structured in a way that supports future growth

Act like a senior frontend engineer and prioritize clarity, maintainability, and scalability in every decision.

## Commit Standards

Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) specification.

### Format

```
<type>(<optional scope>): <short summary>

<optional body>
```

### Types

| Type       | Use when...                                      |
|------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| `feat`     | Adding a new feature or capability               |
| `fix`      | Fixing a bug                                     |
| `refactor` | Restructuring code without changing behaviour    |
| `style`    | Formatting, whitespace, or cosmetic-only changes |
| `docs`     | Documentation-only changes                       |
| `test`     | Adding or updating tests                         |
| `chore`    | Build config, tooling, dependency updates        |
| `perf`     | Performance improvements                         |

### Rules

- Summary must be lowercase, imperative mood, and under 72 characters (e.g. `feat(resolver): add cycle detection`).
- Do **not** end the summary with a period.
- Use the body to explain *why* the change was made when the summary alone is not enough.
- Reference related issues when applicable (e.g. `Closes #12`).
- Each commit should represent a single logical change — avoid bundling unrelated work.
